Table.name: CC_F_ACTUALS_QUEUE_INTERVAL
Table.comment:
PP_F_ACTUALS_QUEUE_INTERVAL is the fact table for interval metrics actuals related to a contact queue. This table allows for variable intervals depending on the configuration of the ACD (e.g. 15, 30, or 60 minute intervals).

The data source for this table are the CC_S_ACD_INTERVAL and CC_S_WFM_INTERVAL staging tables.

Column.name: F_CALL_CENTER_ACTLS_INTRVL_ID
Column.comment: Surrogate key for interval records

Column.name: D_DATE
Column.comment: FK to PP_D_DATES. This column identifies which date the interval data is associated with.

Column.name: D_PROJECT_ID
Column.comment: FK to PP_D_PROJECT. This column indicates which project and segment the interval data is associated with.

Column.name: D_PROGRAM_ID
Column.comment: FK to PP_D_PROGRAM. This column indicates which program the interval data is associated with.

Column.name: D_GEOGRAPHY_MASTER_ID
Column.comment: FK to PP_D_GEOGRAPHY_MASTER. This column indicates the site and geographical location of the interval data.

Column.name: D_UNIT_OF_WORK_ID
Column.comment: FK to PP_D_UNIT_OF_WORK table. This column identifies which unit of work the interval data is associated with.

Column.name: D_CONTACT_QUEUE_ID
Column.comment: FK to PP_D_CONTACT_QUEUE table. This column identifies which contact queue the interval data is associated with.

Column.name: D_INTERVAL_ID
Column.comment: FK to PP_D_INTERVAL. This column identifies which time span the interval data is associated with.

Column.name: D_AGENT_ID
Column.comment: FK to D_AGENT. This field indicates which agent the metrics are associated with.

Column.name: CONTACTS_RECEIVED_FROM_IVR
Column.comment: The total number of contacts received from the IVR for this contact queue during the interval.

Column.name: CONTACTS_OFFERED
Column.comment: The total number of contacts transferred to this queue during the interval.

Column.name: CONTACTS_HANDLED
Column.comment: Total number of contacts that were responded by an agent. Contacts Handled + Contacts Abandoned = Contacts Offered.

Column.name: CONTACTS_ABANDONED
Column.comment: Total number of contacts answered by the ACD system then disconnected by the caller or incorrectly dropped by the system. Abandonment Rate = Contacts Abandoned / Contacts Offered.

Column.name: MIN_HANDLE_TIME
Column.comment: Shortest length of time an agent spent processing a contact (Handle Time = Agent’s Talk Time + Hold Time + Wrap Time)

Column.name: MAX_HANDLE_TIME
Column.comment: Longest length of time an agent spent processing a contact (Handle Time = Agent’s Talk Time + Hold Time + Wrap Time)

Column.name: MEAN_HANDLE_TIME
Column.comment: Average length of time an agent spent processing a contact (Handle Time = Agent’s Talk Time + Hold Time + Wrap Time)

Column.name: MEDIAN_HANDLE_TIME
Column.comment: Middle length of time an agent spent processing a contact (Handle Time = Agent’s Talk Time + Hold Time + Wrap Time)

Column.name: STDDEV_HANDLE_TIME
Column.comment: Variation from the average length of time an agent spent processing a contact (Handle Time = Agent’s Talk Time + Hold Time + Wrap Time)

Column.name: MIN_SPEED_TO_HANDLE
Column.comment: Shortest length of time a contact stayed in the contact center system. (Speed to Handle = Time in the IVR + Wait Time + Talk Time + Hold Time)

Column.name: MAX_SPEED_TO_HANDLE
Column.comment: Longest length of time a contact stayed in the contact center system. (Speed to Handle = Time in the IVR + Wait Time + Talk Time + Hold Time)

Column.name: MEAN_SPEED_TO_HANDLE
Column.comment: Average length of time the contacts stayed in the contact center system. (Speed to Handle = Time in the IVR + Wait Time + Talk Time + Hold Time)

Column.name: MEDIAN_SPEED_TO_HANDLE
Column.comment: Middle length of time the contacts stayed in the contact center system. (Speed to Handle = Time in the IVR + Wait Time + Talk Time + Hold Time)

Column.name: STDDEV_SPEED_TO_HANDLE
Column.comment: Variation from the average length of time the contacts stayed in the contact center system. (Speed to Handle = Time in the IVR + Wait Time + Talk Time + Hold Time)

Column.name: MIN_SPEED_OF_ANSWER
Column.comment: Shortest length of time a contact spent in the queue before talking to an agent. Typically high abandonment rate is associated with long wait time (Speed of Answer).

Column.name: MAX_SPEED_OF_ANSWER
Column.comment: Longest length of time a contact spent in the queue before talking to an agent. Typically high abandonment rate is associated with long wait time (Speed of Answer).

Column.name: MEAN_SPEED_OF_ANSWER
Column.comment: Average length of time the contacts spent in the queue before talking to an agent. Typically high abandonment rate is associated with long wait time (Speed of Answer).

Column.name: MEDIAN_SPEED_OF_ANSWER
Column.comment: Middle length of time the contacts spent in the queue before talking to an agent. Typically high abandonment rate is associated with long wait time (Speed of Answer).

Column.name: STDDEV_SPEED_OF_ANSWER
Column.comment: Variation from the average length of time the contacts spent in the queue before talking to an agent. Typically high abandonment rate is associated with long wait time (Speed of Answer).

Column.name: LABOR_MINUTES_TOTAL
Column.comment:
Total staff minutes at work, including all staff on the payroll. At any time instance, Labor Minutes Total = Labor Minutes Available + Labor Minutes Unavailable.

The default data source for this should be the WFM, but may come from the ACD.

Column.name: LABOR_MINUTES_AVAILABLE
Column.comment: Total staff logged on time (minutes), or time spent in available state waiting for a customer contact. Also called ready time.

Column.name: LABOR_MINUTES_WAITING
Column.comment:
Total minutes that staff logged on but not handling contacts. The percent of labor wait time (among total paid time) may indicate how effective the staff are scheduled at each time interval (daily, hourly, or 15 minutes interval). However, the service target will set a limit on the total minimum wait time, i.e., a very good service level requires “more wait time” to be built into the schedule in order for that service level to be achievable.

The default data source for this should be the WFM, but may come from the ACD.

Column.name: HEADCOUNT_TOTAL
Column.comment: Number of staff on payroll, regardless of status. At any time instance, Total Headcount = Headcount Available + Headcount Unavailable. However, the above equation may not hold for a time interval.

Column.name: HEADCOUNT_AVAILABLE
Column.comment:
Number of staff who logged on. Headcount Available / Total Headcount indicates how well staff is utilized.

The default data source for this should be the WFM, but may come from the ACD.

Column.name: HEADCOUNT_UNAVAILABLE
Column.comment: Number of staff who logged out for any reason, e.g., headcount in vacation, FMLA, trainings and meetings.

Column.name: CONTACT_INVENTORY
Column.comment:
Items received/tasks created but is either work in progress or has not been started.

This column is applicable only if items/tasks are managed as a queue within the ACD.

Column.name: CONTACT_INVENTORY_JEOPARDY
Column.comment:
Total number of work items that are at risk of missing service target.

This column is applicable only if work items are managed as a queue within the ACD.

Column.name: MIN_CONTACT_INVENTORY_AGE
Column.comment:
Lowest number of days an item (task) has been received (created) but has not been completed or cancelled

This column is applicable only if items are managed as a queue within the ACD.

Column.name: MAX_CONTACT_INVENTORY_AGE
Column.comment:
Highest number of days an item (task) has been received (created) but has not been completed or cancelled.

This column is applicable only if items are managed as a queue within the ACD.

Column.name: MEAN_CONTACT_INVENTORY_AGE
Column.comment:
Average number of days an item (task) has been received (created) but has not been completed or cancelled.

This column is applicable only if items are managed as a queue within the ACD.

Column.name: MEDIAN_CONTACT_INVENTORY_AGE
Column.comment:
Middle number of days an item (task) has been received (created) but has not been completed or cancelled.

This column is applicable only if items are managed as a queue within the ACD.

Column.name: STDDEV_CONTACT_INVENTORY_AGE
Column.comment:
Variation from the average number of days an item (task) has been received (created) but has not been completed or cancelled.

This column is applicable only if items are managed as a queue within the ACD.

Column.name: CONTACTS_TRANSFERRED
Column.comment: Contacts that were rerouted or escalated to another agent or skill group. Examples include calls that start in a sales queue but really need to be handled by technical support.

Column.name: OUTFLOW_CONTACTS
Column.comment: Total number of contacts queued to multiple skill group or applications

Column.name: ANSWER_WAIT_TIME_TOTAL
Column.comment: Total wait time spent in a queue for all calls that were answered in the reporting interval. This is used to calculate the average speed of answer.

Column.name: ABANDON_TIME_TOTAL
Column.comment: Total time spent in agent queues for all calls that were abandoned in a reporting interval.

Column.name: TALK_TIME_TOTAL
Column.comment: The time agents spend with a customer. Does not include hold time or ACW time.

Column.name: AFTER_CALL_WORK_TIME_TOTAL
Column.comment: Time spent completing the transaction after the customer has been released or disconnected. Time spent after a customer call or chat until the agent state changes places them in idle or ready. This is a component of Average Handle Time.

Column.name: SERVICE_LEVEL_ANSWERED_PERCENT
Column.comment: Percent of calls answered within answer time threshold. Examples include the wait times for an inbound call to get answered, a web chat to be responded to, or a service dispatch to be initiated. It indicates what percent of the transactions begin processing on or before a defined wait time (usually expressed in seconds). E.g., for service level 75/120, the first number is the target for the percent of transactions handled and the second number is the cycle time target, typically expressed in seconds. So 75/120 means the target is 75% of the transactions are processed on or before 120 seconds.

Column.name: SERVICE_LEVEL_ANSWERED_COUNT
Column.comment: Total number of calls answered within the service level threshold during the reporting interval

Column.name: SERVICE_LEVEL_ABANDONED
Column.comment: Abandonment Rate = Calls Abandon / Calls Offered. Reflects customer patience level for wait and how adequately a contact center is staffed.

Column.name: CALLS_ON_HOLD
Column.comment: Number of contacts put on hold at least once during the reporting interval.

Column.name: HOLD_TIME_TOTAL
Column.comment: Total time for all calls being on hold during the reporting interval. Used to calculate average hold time (and indirectly, average handle time) for a reporting interval.

Column.name: SHORT_ABANDONS
Column.comment: Total number of calls to the route that were too short to be considered abandoned during the reporting interval

Column.name: CONTACTS_BLOCKED
Column.comment: Number of contacts that are not allowed into the system due to trunk capacity or system issues.

Column.name: CREATE_DATE
Column.comment: Date this record was inserted into the staging table. This is used for audit purposes.

Column.name: LAST_UPDATE_DATE
Column.comment: Date this record was last updated. This is used for audit purposes.
